Deputy President William Ruto yesterday asked Opposition politicians not to criticise NASA leader Raila Odinga for agreeing to meet President Uhuru Kenyatta last week. Ruto said the meeting was for the good of the country. He urged NASA co-principals Kalonzo Musyoka, Musalia Mudavadi and Moses Wetang’ula to join the reconciliation calls to unite the country. “I want to ask those who are yet to join us to come so that we can take this country forward,” Ruto said. Read: Not consulted? Accept and support unity pact, Ruto tells Nasa principals Speaking at Njoro Anglican Inland Church in Nakuru during an interdenominational service, Ruto said Uhuru and Raila’s meeting will boost the efforts to unite Kenyans. “The journey to unite Kenyans began in Nakuru with President Kenyatta and myself in 2013. What happened on Friday was a culmination of that effort of bringing Kenyans together,” Ruto said. Earlier, Ruto opened the Njoro CDF office and another for the area OCPD in Njoro town. The DP said Jubilee was ready to work with all leaders to transform the country. “I assure you that we will unite as leaders to fulfill the Jubilee manifesto,” Ruto said. Read: Go slow on Raila over unity pact, Ruto tells Nasa principals He was accompanied by Governors Lee Kinyanjui (Nakuru), Francis Kimemia (Nyandarua), Nakuru Senator Susan Kihika, MPs Kuria Kimani (Molo), Charity Kathambi (Njoro), Martha Wangari (Gilgil), Joseph Tanui (Kuresoi South), Samuel Arama (Nakuru Town West ), Kimani Ngunjiri (Bahati), Ndindi Nyoro (Kiharu), Kinuthia Gachobe (Subukia), Moses Kuria (Gatundu South), Joash Nyamoko (North Mugirango), Rehema Dida (Isiolo), Liza Chelule (Nakuru) and Mpuri Aburi (EALA). Kuria welcomed Raila’s decision to join hands with Uhuru to end political divisions in the country. Arama urged other Opposition politicians to work with the government for development. Related: Kalonzo, Wetangula meet ahead of Nasa summit on Monday   Click here for the latest political news